00:39:24.230 --> 00:39:25.880
too, is that it's individual.

00:39:25.880 --> 00:39:29.640
And it shows discipline
and toughness.

00:39:29.640 --> 00:39:32.830
And that appeals to people.

00:39:32.830 --> 00:39:35.490
And they identify it
with these men and women.

00:39:35.490 --> 00:39:37.240
JASON KRUEGER: And we
were talking earlier

00:39:37.240 --> 00:39:39.950
about the education
level of the fan base.

00:39:39.950 --> 00:39:43.190
And you know, of course,
whoever tuned in 1993

00:39:43.190 --> 00:39:47.345
was either a pro wrestling
fan or maybe they were

00:39:47.345 --> 00:39:49.410
a martial artists themselves.

00:39:49.410 --> 00:39:53.100
But through the 90s and the
2000s, and probably even mostly

00:39:53.100 --> 00:39:56.260
today, the average fan
still wants to see blood.

00:39:56.260 --> 00:39:57.690
They want to see knockouts.

00:39:57.690 --> 00:40:00.880
And I still think, personally,
as a jiu-jitsu player,

00:40:00.880 --> 00:40:04.112
I appreciate the small
technical details.

00:40:04.112 --> 00:40:06.320
When it looks like two people
are just, like, hugging

00:40:06.320 --> 00:40:08.030
and doing nothing
on the ground, I'm

00:40:08.030 --> 00:40:10.610
looking to see the
angles they're going for,

00:40:10.610 --> 00:40:13.270
and how they're countering
those angles and recountering.

00:40:13.270 --> 00:40:15.130
But the truth is
the UFC is still

00:40:15.130 --> 00:40:17.990
is trying to attract
those big Irish fan

00:40:17.990 --> 00:40:20.750
bases that want to see Conor
McGregor knock someone out.

00:40:20.750 --> 00:40:25.510
And over time, I think it will
evolve to have some variance.

00:40:25.510 --> 00:40:29.720
But there still is the core
of it, you know, blood lust.

00:40:29.720 --> 00:40:31.791
I don't know how you
would stack rank, like,

00:40:31.791 --> 00:40:33.040
the best and the worst of MMA.

00:40:33.040 --> 00:40:34.470
We talked a little earlier.

00:40:34.470 --> 00:40:37.330
What would be, in your
opinion, the best elements

00:40:37.330 --> 00:40:39.599
of what Mixed Martial
Arts bring in?

00:40:39.599 --> 00:40:41.932
And what would be something
that's, probably, the worst?

00:40:41.932 --> 00:40:43.860
DOUG MERLINO: I
think the best is,

00:40:43.860 --> 00:40:50.260
for me, is that you see really
the extremes of what humans

00:40:50.260 --> 00:40:53.340
can do, in some ways,
in these fights.

00:40:53.340 --> 00:40:56.330
There are some fights where
the fighters are really,

00:40:56.330 --> 00:41:01.590
really tested to
beyond any level

00:41:01.590 --> 00:41:04.370
that you would think
a person could endure.

00:41:04.370 --> 00:41:05.640
And they still come back.

00:41:05.640 --> 00:41:09.840
And I've seen it on TV.

00:41:09.840 --> 00:41:11.940
And I've seen it with
guys that I followed.

00:41:11.940 --> 00:41:18.620
And you know what they've gone
through and the amount of pain

00:41:18.620 --> 00:41:22.960
and mental toughness that
it would take to keep

00:41:22.960 --> 00:41:26.330
going in that situation.

00:41:26.330 --> 00:41:28.060
For me, personally,
it's inspiring.

00:41:30.880 --> 00:41:32.640
And it's partly
inspiring because it

00:41:32.640 --> 00:41:34.300
is on a very brutal level.

00:41:34.300 --> 00:41:39.550
I mean, you're getting beat
up, and still keep going.

00:41:39.550 --> 00:41:44.420
So you know, it's really a test
of human endurance and skill.

00:41:44.420 --> 00:41:47.470
And then, I've been
to certain fights

00:41:47.470 --> 00:41:49.920
where there is a high
level of blood lost.

00:41:49.920 --> 00:41:53.046
And like we were
saying earlier, I

00:41:53.046 --> 00:41:54.420
don't know if
that's good or bad.

00:41:54.420 --> 00:42:01.290
I think it's part of this
whole sport because, you know,

00:42:01.290 --> 00:42:04.530
it's really combat that's
ritualized inside a cage.

00:42:04.530 --> 00:42:06.325
And you have rules,
and you have a referee.

00:42:09.290 --> 00:42:11.180
But I mean, really,
it's human combat.

00:42:11.180 --> 00:42:15.590
And it's something that we have
done for thousands of years.

00:42:15.590 --> 00:42:18.140
But I think it should
bring about mixed emotions

00:42:18.140 --> 00:42:20.840
because you do see these
great sides of people.

00:42:20.840 --> 00:42:24.810
And you see a lot of
blood lust and desire

00:42:24.810 --> 00:42:29.440
to see someone get
knocked out or whatever.

00:42:29.440 --> 00:42:35.630
And I think that's actually part
and parcel of the sport there.

00:42:35.630 --> 00:42:40.640
Like, it's part of human nature.

00:42:40.640 --> 00:42:42.590
I think the same with
football or hockey, too.

00:42:42.590 --> 00:42:44.780
Like, you can say
I watch football

00:42:44.780 --> 00:42:48.110
for the skill of Peyton
Manning or Tom Brady.

00:42:48.110 --> 00:42:50.770
But a lot people like
to see big hits, too.

00:42:50.770 --> 00:42:53.340
And if I look inside
myself, I like to see skill.

00:42:53.340 --> 00:42:57.300
And then, there is a
part of being a human

00:42:57.300 --> 00:43:00.310
that it's amazing
to see violence

00:43:00.310 --> 00:43:04.480
that's very skillfully
and forcefully applied.

00:43:04.480 --> 00:43:06.810
I mean, not that that's
necessarily good or bad.

00:43:06.810 --> 00:43:08.720
It just, kind of, is.

00:43:08.720 --> 00:43:10.630
But I found myself,
a times, at fights

00:43:10.630 --> 00:43:12.630
feeling a bit uncomfortable
because it was like,

00:43:12.630 --> 00:43:16.140
whoa, this crowd is really
revved up for blood.

00:43:16.140 --> 00:43:18.050
This doesn't feel good.

00:43:18.050 --> 00:43:21.354
JASON KRUEGER: Yeah, I feel like
I started at a small MMA gym.

00:43:21.354 --> 00:43:23.020
They trained a little
bit of everything.

00:43:23.020 --> 00:43:25.290
And I did the Filipino
[INAUDIBLE] stick

00:43:25.290 --> 00:43:29.720
fighting or the kickboxing and
started getting really into it.

00:43:29.720 --> 00:43:31.915
And then, they finally
put you into sparring.

00:43:31.915 --> 00:43:33.870
And you got the pads
and the head gear on.

00:43:33.870 --> 00:43:36.022
But even then, it was like
the first couple times,

00:43:36.022 --> 00:43:37.230
you just get hit in the nose.

00:43:37.230 --> 00:43:38.146
And your eyes tear up.

00:43:38.146 --> 00:43:43.074
And you're like this is not
as fun as I thought it looked.

00:43:43.074 --> 00:43:44.490
And that's kind
of where I quickly

00:43:44.490 --> 00:43:47.690
gravitated to jiu-jitsu because
it's like you can actually

00:43:47.690 --> 00:43:49.940
test it without getting hurt.

00:43:49.940 --> 00:43:53.960
And for that, I think that's
one of the reasons why jiu-jitsu

00:43:53.960 --> 00:43:55.800
was the catalyst for all this.

00:43:55.800 --> 00:43:58.920
It's a sport that you can
train at a very high level,

00:43:58.920 --> 00:44:01.825
consistently, on a daily
basis where you can find out

00:44:01.825 --> 00:44:04.200
what works and doesn't work
without hurting your training

00:44:04.200 --> 00:44:05.010
partner.

00:44:05.010 --> 00:44:09.010
And one of the things,
the fan base kind of just

00:44:09.010 --> 00:44:10.890
gravitates to
their own interest.

00:44:10.890 --> 00:44:13.310
Some fans join a boxing
gym after watching the UFC

00:44:13.310 --> 00:44:14.200
for awhile.

00:44:14.200 --> 00:44:16.224
But at my academy
where we train,

00:44:16.224 --> 00:44:17.390
people come in all the time.

00:44:17.390 --> 00:44:20.180
And they say, is this
UFC, or what is this?

00:44:20.180 --> 00:44:21.690
And they're wrestlers,
for example.

00:44:21.690 --> 00:44:25.080
And over time, if you
start to gravitate

00:44:25.080 --> 00:44:28.430
towards a specific art, you
just kind of go to those gyms.

00:44:28.430 --> 00:44:30.480
And I think that's
the best part of this

00:44:30.480 --> 00:44:34.750
is getting young kids to
train jiu-jitsu, or learn

00:44:34.750 --> 00:44:37.700
self-defense, and be inspired
by those role models, for sure.

00:44:37.700 --> 00:44:38.735
I think that's the best.

00:44:38.735 --> 00:44:39.610
And I agree with you.

00:44:39.610 --> 00:44:43.260
The worst is,
unfortunately, I fully

00:44:43.260 --> 00:44:45.780
admit I do want to see
Conor McGregor knock out

00:44:45.780 --> 00:44:46.530
his next opponent.

00:44:46.530 --> 00:44:49.710
Like, I'm super excited
to see him do it.

00:44:49.710 --> 00:44:52.080
So I do have to sit
down and say, well, I

00:44:52.080 --> 00:44:53.930
agree that it's a
technical sport.

00:44:53.930 --> 00:44:56.610
There's definitely blood.

00:44:56.610 --> 00:44:59.340
And it's violence at its core.

00:44:59.340 --> 00:45:02.890
It's the most pure form of
sport and the most for pure form

00:45:02.890 --> 00:45:04.910
of fighting, really.

