00:48:04.990 --> 00:48:07.580
that might sound a little
weird, but I really believe in,

00:48:07.580 --> 00:48:10.620
is that not just when
one is getting physically

00:48:10.620 --> 00:48:13.310
attacked but, more
often, we're going

00:48:13.310 --> 00:48:18.650
to be verbally or mentally
attacked or some other type

00:48:18.650 --> 00:48:20.201
of aggression.

00:48:20.201 --> 00:48:21.700
That's going to be
much more common,

00:48:21.700 --> 00:48:23.390
I think, for everyone here.

00:48:23.390 --> 00:48:25.690
And I think doing any
martial arts helps

00:48:25.690 --> 00:48:29.120
you get more confidence
and belief in yourself

00:48:29.120 --> 00:48:30.790
so that, if you are
in that situation,

00:48:30.790 --> 00:48:32.070
you're much more calm.

00:48:32.070 --> 00:48:34.820
And you can respond
in a way that

00:48:34.820 --> 00:48:36.710
doesn't escalate
and doesn't get in--

00:48:36.710 --> 00:48:38.930
or you don't have to freak out.

00:48:38.930 --> 00:48:41.610
So I think, oddly, that's
another type of self-defense

00:48:41.610 --> 00:48:45.204
that you can learn from whatever
martial art you want to do.

00:48:45.204 --> 00:48:47.370
JASON KRUEGER: Yeah, I mean
even something like yoga

00:48:47.370 --> 00:48:51.510
where learning how to
breathe in awkward positions

00:48:51.510 --> 00:48:52.840
with good posture.

00:48:52.840 --> 00:48:55.624
You know, you look at videos
of kids getting bullied,

00:48:55.624 --> 00:48:57.290
it's usually the kid
that's hunched over

00:48:57.290 --> 00:49:00.430
and like, kind of, you
know, don't, stop, stop.

00:49:00.430 --> 00:49:02.900
But the kid stands up
and he's been familiar

00:49:02.900 --> 00:49:07.470
with the basic Judo throws and
done it hundreds or thousands

00:49:07.470 --> 00:49:09.510
of times, it just
builds that confidence

00:49:09.510 --> 00:49:10.760
because you know I'm
going to stand tall.

00:49:10.760 --> 00:49:11.968
And I'm not going to take it.

00:49:11.968 --> 00:49:14.070
So I think whatever you
can practice most often.

00:49:16.990 --> 00:49:20.860
After hanging out with
fighters for two years,

00:49:20.860 --> 00:49:23.080
what surprised you the most
of the life of a fighter?

00:49:23.080 --> 00:49:26.340
I think we touched
on that quite a bit.

00:49:26.340 --> 00:49:29.870
Are there any unrelated skills,
such as yoga or gymnastics,

00:49:29.870 --> 00:49:32.370
that you'd recommend to
Brazilian jiu-jitsu enthusiasts

00:49:32.370 --> 00:49:34.916
to explore?

00:49:34.916 --> 00:49:36.459
DOUG MERLINO: I
think yoga's great.

00:49:36.459 --> 00:49:37.750
That's just a personal opinion.

00:49:37.750 --> 00:49:39.550
JASON KRUEGER: Yeah,
I think just what

00:49:39.550 --> 00:49:40.990
yoga or Pilates offer.

00:49:40.990 --> 00:49:43.640
I actually practice both as
a complement to jiu-jitsu.

00:49:43.640 --> 00:49:46.260
It's just movement
and flexibility

00:49:46.260 --> 00:49:48.920
are great for injury prevention.

00:49:48.920 --> 00:49:50.240
I've been injured a bunch.

00:49:50.240 --> 00:49:53.120
And I've even stopped
training for many months

00:49:53.120 --> 00:49:56.090
at a time and only trained
Pilates after a bad injury.

00:49:56.090 --> 00:49:57.966
And I came back, and
I was actually better.

00:49:57.966 --> 00:49:59.340
Like, my hips were
more flexible.

00:49:59.340 --> 00:50:02.494
And it felt like I can be more
comfortable to avoid bad spots.

00:50:02.494 --> 00:50:04.410
So I would definitely
recommend both of those.

00:50:04.410 --> 00:50:07.340
I think gymnastics
is wide ranging.

00:50:07.340 --> 00:50:09.520
But I don't know if I have
enough experience to say.

00:50:12.465 --> 00:50:14.090
Can you scroll down
a little bit to see

00:50:14.090 --> 00:50:15.450
what the next question is?

00:50:17.834 --> 00:50:19.250
I think you touched
on this a bit.

00:50:19.250 --> 00:50:21.166
But what generally happens
to the fighters who

00:50:21.166 --> 00:50:24.345
don't make it to the big time?

00:50:24.345 --> 00:50:25.935
DOUG MERLINO: They get a job.

00:50:25.935 --> 00:50:29.170
[LAUGHTER]

00:50:29.170 --> 00:50:30.520
You know, it depends.

00:50:30.520 --> 00:50:33.480
A lot of the fighters come
from college wrestling.

00:50:33.480 --> 00:50:38.190
So they might have a degree.

00:50:38.190 --> 00:50:39.400
It's hard one, you know.

00:50:39.400 --> 00:50:41.552
One guy I got very close
to was a college wrestler.

00:50:41.552 --> 00:50:42.510
And he'd been fighting.

00:50:42.510 --> 00:50:44.150
His career was ending.

00:50:44.150 --> 00:50:46.860
And this is just like
a personal anecdote,

00:50:46.860 --> 00:50:48.320
but he was freaked out.

00:50:48.320 --> 00:50:49.320
He was in his 30s.

00:50:49.320 --> 00:50:50.980
And he was like, everyone else
is getting married, and having

00:50:50.980 --> 00:50:51.930
kids, and has a house.

00:50:51.930 --> 00:50:53.130
And I'm broke.

00:50:53.130 --> 00:50:54.420
I've been following my dream.

00:50:54.420 --> 00:50:55.670
And what am I going to do now?

00:50:55.670 --> 00:50:56.550
And we're friends.

00:50:56.550 --> 00:50:58.600
So I catch up with
him from time to time.

00:50:58.600 --> 00:51:02.050
And now he's been working
as a personal trainer.

00:51:02.050 --> 00:51:04.920
And now he's trying to
get his own gym going.

00:51:04.920 --> 00:51:06.960
A lot of these guys
are physical people.

00:51:06.960 --> 00:51:10.320
So they'll probably end up doing
something along those lines.

00:51:10.320 --> 00:51:14.630
But it's not easy because
where other people are building

00:51:14.630 --> 00:51:18.330
their careers over their
20s and early 30s, by 35,

00:51:18.330 --> 00:51:19.550
your career is done.

00:51:19.550 --> 00:51:21.750
So it's really hard
for all of them.

00:51:21.750 --> 00:51:25.130
I mean, I don't know any fighter
who really transitions that

00:51:25.130 --> 00:51:25.630
well.

00:51:25.630 --> 00:51:27.754
JASON KRUEGER: Yeah, and
it's not just the fighters

00:51:27.754 --> 00:51:28.670
that don't make it.

00:51:28.670 --> 00:51:31.080
But there's plenty of
examples of fighters

00:51:31.080 --> 00:51:34.600
that just make a conscious
decision to get out early.

00:51:34.600 --> 00:51:36.870
George St. Pierre, who
you talked about earlier,

00:51:36.870 --> 00:51:39.370
he was on a number
of radio interviews

00:51:39.370 --> 00:51:42.470
and talking about how he's
having horrible headaches.

00:51:42.470 --> 00:51:45.700
And he's known for not
taking tons of damage.

00:51:45.700 --> 00:51:48.390
And even he is saying
he might be done.

00:51:48.390 --> 00:51:49.890
I think he's talk
about coming back.

00:51:49.890 --> 00:51:52.160
But I think it's worth noting
that it's not just the fighters

00:51:52.160 --> 00:51:52.951
that don't make it.

00:51:52.951 --> 00:51:55.280
It's the fighters that
make a decision that

00:51:55.280 --> 00:51:59.550
is it worth the five years of
damage to maybe make it or not.

00:51:59.550 --> 00:52:01.450
So some just make the
decision to get out.

00:52:01.450 --> 00:52:03.920
And in those cases, they
could be trainers themselves

00:52:03.920 --> 00:52:04.795
or go somewhere else.

00:52:04.795 --> 00:52:06.378
DOUG MERLINO: Yeah,
and unfortunately,

00:52:06.378 --> 00:52:08.020
a very common thing
is guys who've

00:52:08.020 --> 00:52:12.998
actually made it and done really
well still leave with no money.

00:52:12.998 --> 00:52:16.210
JASON KRUEGER: The last
