00:53:56.852 --> 00:53:58.440
AUDIENCE: Yeah,
just one question.

00:53:58.440 --> 00:54:00.900
So I'm just curious
about your experience

00:54:00.900 --> 00:54:04.440
when you were witnessing
these people train.

00:54:04.440 --> 00:54:07.320
Are there any new
entrants or maybe people

00:54:07.320 --> 00:54:10.420
leaving from more purist
places, which, honestly, I

00:54:10.420 --> 00:54:14.333
thought all the martial
arts were advocating only

00:54:14.333 --> 00:54:16.166
doing one thing would
have shut down by now.

00:54:16.166 --> 00:54:17.260
But they're still going.

00:54:17.260 --> 00:54:19.360
But are there new people
arriving and bringing

00:54:19.360 --> 00:54:20.130
new elements?

00:54:20.130 --> 00:54:22.430
And maybe, are
they experimenting

00:54:22.430 --> 00:54:26.560
with something new that we're
not seeing in the fights yet?

00:54:26.560 --> 00:54:32.530
DOUG MERLINO: You know,
it goes up and down.

00:54:32.530 --> 00:54:35.360
And for a number
of years, wrestlers

00:54:35.360 --> 00:54:38.165
were really dominating
the sport because they

00:54:38.165 --> 00:54:39.040
have that background.

00:54:39.040 --> 00:54:41.350
And they can get in close
and use their physicality

00:54:41.350 --> 00:54:46.130
to control and hold someone, and
punch them, or throw them down.

00:54:46.130 --> 00:54:48.890
And then, apply a jiu-jitsu
move or something.

00:54:48.890 --> 00:54:50.810
And it's funny.

00:54:50.810 --> 00:54:52.970
A couple years ago, one
of the striking coaches

00:54:52.970 --> 00:54:55.357
at the gym-- of
course, he's bias

00:54:55.357 --> 00:54:57.690
because he's a striking coach--
but he was like, really,

00:54:57.690 --> 00:55:02.500
the next thing is going to
be more striking techniques.

00:55:02.500 --> 00:55:05.230
Like, you're seeing these
weird spinning kicks

00:55:05.230 --> 00:55:05.990
and other things.

00:55:05.990 --> 00:55:07.830
And guys are really
going to raise

00:55:07.830 --> 00:55:11.310
the level of their striking.

00:55:11.310 --> 00:55:15.214
And I think with someone
like Conor McGregor,

00:55:15.214 --> 00:55:16.380
you're starting to see that.

00:55:16.380 --> 00:55:18.230
He's great at movement.

00:55:18.230 --> 00:55:20.360
You see how he's moving around.

00:55:20.360 --> 00:55:22.350
His strikes are coming
from all angles.

00:55:22.350 --> 00:55:27.720
So I think what this coach
was saying to me it's true.

00:55:27.720 --> 00:55:30.036
Like, there's developments.

00:55:30.036 --> 00:55:32.650
And when one side gets
dominant, like wrestling,

00:55:32.650 --> 00:55:34.670
and then you have a
bunch of wrestlers,

00:55:34.670 --> 00:55:39.270
then there's a new space
for other techniques.

00:55:39.270 --> 00:55:41.519
So I think striking
is where there's

00:55:41.519 --> 00:55:42.560
a lot of new development.

00:55:42.560 --> 00:55:44.854
But it's more tweaking
rather than anything.

00:55:44.854 --> 00:55:46.270
I mean, I think
what you're seeing

00:55:46.270 --> 00:55:47.330
is now a lot of tweaking.

00:55:47.330 --> 00:55:52.960
Another thing is just more fluid
melding between all the styles

00:55:52.960 --> 00:55:55.750
that you get from people who've
trained it from a young age.

00:55:55.750 --> 00:55:57.250
JASON KRUEGER: The
one thing I'd add

00:55:57.250 --> 00:55:59.900
is, for one, there's not
just fighting techniques.

00:55:59.900 --> 00:56:03.110
But there's weight cutting
techniques, for example.

00:56:03.110 --> 00:56:06.255
You know, there's fighters--
for example, Carlos Condit.

00:56:06.255 --> 00:56:07.934
I recently listened
to an interview

00:56:07.934 --> 00:56:08.850
he had with Joe Rogan.

00:56:08.850 --> 00:56:11.620
And he was talking about
how, early in his career,

00:56:11.620 --> 00:56:14.700
he would be like eight
pounds away four days out.

00:56:14.700 --> 00:56:16.510
And he'd freak out,
and stop eating.

00:56:16.510 --> 00:56:19.510
And then, the day of the fight,
has completely burned himself

00:56:19.510 --> 00:56:20.850
of energy reserves.

00:56:20.850 --> 00:56:23.040
And now he's working
with just a diet

00:56:23.040 --> 00:56:26.110
coach that helps him with
preparations for that weight

00:56:26.110 --> 00:56:26.610
cut.

00:56:26.610 --> 00:56:29.580
So he's actually eating
reasonably large quantities

00:56:29.580 --> 00:56:34.240
of food 24 and 18 hours out and
naturally drops that weight.

00:56:34.240 --> 00:56:37.060
Just touches down on
his weigh in moment

00:56:37.060 --> 00:56:38.660
and then goes right back up.

00:56:38.660 --> 00:56:40.890
And they're monitoring
them with technology

00:56:40.890 --> 00:56:42.350
to make sure they're
not dehydrated

00:56:42.350 --> 00:56:43.766
in the brain and
things like that.

00:56:43.766 --> 00:56:46.970
So I think a lot more,
at least right now,

00:56:46.970 --> 00:56:49.730
is being focused on
how to actually prepare

00:56:49.730 --> 00:56:52.301
for fights physically,
which complements,

00:56:52.301 --> 00:56:53.550
of course, all the techniques.

00:56:53.550 --> 00:56:55.000
That's happening a lot.

00:56:55.000 --> 00:56:58.510
And just to mention Conor
McGregor, him and even Carlos

00:56:58.510 --> 00:57:02.500
are actually training less
or sparring less and doing

00:57:02.500 --> 00:57:03.850
complementary exercises.

00:57:03.850 --> 00:57:06.090
They work with movement
coaches that deal

00:57:06.090 --> 00:57:08.360
with balance and coordination.

00:57:08.360 --> 00:57:10.369
The same thing with
the old methods

00:57:10.369 --> 00:57:11.910
of train, train,
train, train, train.

00:57:11.910 --> 00:57:14.570
It turns out that more
is, sometimes, less.

00:57:14.570 --> 00:57:18.320
So I think a there's lot
of recent revelations

00:57:18.320 --> 00:57:20.970
in that space, for sure.

00:57:20.970 --> 00:57:23.470
I think We have time for, maybe,
one more question if anyone

00:57:23.470 --> 00:57:25.220
has one or two.

00:57:28.148 --> 00:57:31.566
AUDIENCE: I'm taking
this spot again.

00:57:31.566 --> 00:57:35.490
In training, these people at the
top level, what did you witness

00:57:35.490 --> 00:57:38.630
were the most common
types of injuries?

00:57:38.630 --> 00:57:39.470
I mean training.

00:57:39.470 --> 00:57:40.910
I don't mean in the fight.

00:57:40.910 --> 00:57:41.050
Obviously, they get destroyed.

00:57:41.050 --> 00:57:41.841
DOUG MERLINO: Yeah.

00:57:44.180 --> 00:57:48.270
Yeah, the injuries
happened all the time.

00:57:48.270 --> 00:57:50.070
Every single guy I
followed, everyone,

00:57:50.070 --> 00:57:52.390
was injured during
the time I was there.

00:57:56.764 --> 00:57:58.180
And we're not
talking head injury.

00:57:58.180 --> 00:58:01.160
We're talking things
that come with wrestling,

00:58:01.160 --> 00:58:03.930
and going to the ground,
and getting your head

00:58:03.930 --> 00:58:04.580
tweaked around.

00:58:04.580 --> 00:58:07.730
So there was neck
injuries a lot.

00:58:07.730 --> 00:58:12.240
Shoulders, knee,
and all your joints

00:58:12.240 --> 00:58:15.440
because you're with someone
and you take a tumble.

00:58:15.440 --> 00:58:19.970
And it's really easy
to throw something off.

00:58:24.350 --> 00:58:27.810
So yeah, and a lot
of broken hands.

00:58:30.630 --> 00:58:32.780
Most of the injuries don't
happen in the fights.

00:58:32.780 --> 00:58:34.905
But the one injury that
happens in the fights a lot

00:58:34.905 --> 00:58:38.280
is because they wear the small
gloves that they break a hand.

00:58:38.280 --> 00:58:41.290
And then, apparently,
once you break your hand,

00:58:41.290 --> 00:58:42.741
it's very easy to
break it again.

00:58:42.741 --> 00:58:43.740
JASON KRUEGER: And feet.

00:58:43.740 --> 00:58:45.050
I mean, hand and feet.

00:58:45.050 --> 00:58:47.050
Like, there's so many
little bones, they just,

00:58:47.050 --> 00:58:48.220
often, don't recover.

00:58:48.220 --> 00:58:51.930
And a good friend of
mine-- actually, he's

00:58:51.930 --> 00:58:56.490
a trainer for the most recent
world champion in jiu-jitsu.

00:58:56.490 --> 00:58:59.330
And this guy was just
giving a seminar in Brazil

00:58:59.330 --> 00:59:02.495
just before the Brazilian
world championships.

00:59:02.495 --> 00:59:03.970
Like, two days
before, he was just

00:59:03.970 --> 00:59:05.830
sitting on the mat
talking to somebody.

00:59:05.830 --> 00:59:07.980
And somebody just accidentally
rolled over his foot

00:59:07.980 --> 00:59:08.690
and fractured it.

00:59:08.690 --> 00:59:10.440
And it took him months
to recover from it.

00:59:10.440 --> 00:59:13.565
And it's like the things that
are not what you expect usually

00:59:13.565 --> 00:59:14.690
cause the most frustration.

00:59:14.690 --> 00:59:16.398
You know, it would be
one thing if he was

00:59:16.398 --> 00:59:17.590
in a fight or training hard.

00:59:17.590 --> 00:59:18.756
But he's just sitting there.

00:59:18.756 --> 00:59:20.984
And someone rolls on
his foot, and it cracks.

00:59:20.984 --> 00:59:22.400
DOUG MERLINO: And
the other danger

00:59:22.400 --> 00:59:26.532
